<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-11-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/454.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Commanding General,
                                    Department of Texas</gloss>, to The <gloss type="to">Adjutant
                                    General</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                        Antonio</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-11-23"><hi rend="italic">November 23,
                                    1910</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Situation on border much exaggerated in papers. Discreet officers now at
                            El Paso, Del Rio, Eagle Pass, and Laredo have instructions to report by
                            telephone or telegram. There is a decided impression current among
                            people who are conversant with the situation in Mexico that the
                            demonstrations along border are merely to draw attention of Mexican
                            Government away from real points of danger, which they claim will be in
                            the more settled centers of population.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hoyt</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Commanding.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>